package lenses

import "github.com/sw6n297mn8-maker/mesh-spec/architecture/artifact-schemas:artifact_schemas"

temporalModelingForFinancialSystems: artifact_schemas.#AnalyticalLens & {
id:     "lens-temporal-modeling-for-financial-systems"
name:   "Modelagem Temporal para Sistemas Financeiros"

purpose: "Orientar decisões sobre como modelar tempo como primitiva de primeira classe — tipos temporais, settlement, bitemporal, day count, cutoffs e timezone discipline."
status: "draft"

trigger: {
	conditions: [
		"a decisão envolve como o sistema representa, armazena e raciocina sobre tempo em operações financeiras",
		"a decisão envolve como datas de vencimento, janelas de liquidação, períodos de carência ou prazos regulatórios são calculados",
		"a decisão envolve como D+0, D+1, D+2 settlement cycles são modelados com business days corretos",
		"a decisão envolve como reconciliar eventos que aconteceram em momentos diferentes (event time vs processing time vs recording time)",
		"a decisão envolve como lidar com retroatividade (dados recebidos atrasados que afetam operações já processadas)",
		"a decisão envolve como timezone e fuso horário entre participantes são tratados em operações financeiras",
		"a decisão envolve como bitemporal modeling (when-known vs when-happened) é aplicado para auditoria e compliance",
		"a decisão envolve como erros de arredondamento temporal (dia errado, feriado ignorado, timezone incorreto) causam erros financeiros",
		"a decisão envolve como contagem de dias (business/252, actual/360) é usada para cálculo de deságio e precificação",
	]
	keywords: [
		"temporal", "tempo", "time", "datetime", "timestamp",
		"vencimento", "maturity", "due date", "prazo",
		"liquidação", "settlement", "D+0", "D+1", "D+2",
		"dia útil", "business day", "working day",
		"feriado", "holiday", "calendar",
		"timezone", "fuso horário", "UTC", "America/Sao_Paulo",
		"carência", "grace period", "prazo de carência",
		"retroatividade", "late-arriving data", "backdated",
		"bitemporal", "event time", "processing time", "valid time", "transaction time",
		"janela", "window", "cutoff", "horário de corte",
		"accrual", "pro-rata", "contagem de dias", "day count",
		"safra", "vintage", "cohort", "período",
	]
	excludeWhen: [
		"a decisão é sobre event ordering e event sourcing — usar event-driven-architecture-patterns",
		"a decisão é sobre calendário de negócios como abstração i18n — usar internationalization-and-localization-architecture",
		"a decisão é sobre observability e detecção de anomalias em produção — usar observability-operational-intelligence",
		"a decisão é sobre testing de edge cases temporais — usar testing-and-validation-for-financial-systems",
	]
	rationale: "Sistemas financeiros são profundamente temporais. Uma antecipação de recebível envolve: data de emissão da NF, data de vencimento, data de submissão, data de aprovação, data de cessão, data de liquidação, data de pagamento pelo sacado, data de conciliação. Cada uma: em timezone específico, com regras de business day, com cutoffs, com possibilidade de atraso. D+1 settlement significa 1 business day — mas qual calendário? Qual timezone para determinar 'dia'? Qual horário de corte? Erros temporais acumulam: settlement 1 dia errado × 1% das operações × R$50k valor médio × 1.000 ops/mês = R$500k/mês com data incorreta. Juros de 1 dia sobre R$500k: R$200+/mês de custo financeiro invisível. EDA cobre ordenação de eventos. IL cobre BusinessCalendar como abstração i18n. TV cobre testing. Esta lens cobre a semântica financeira do tempo: como modelar, armazenar, calcular e raciocinar sobre tempo como primitiva de primeira classe."
}

concepts: [
	{
		id:         "tm-temporal-primitives"
		name:       "Primitivas Temporais: Os Tipos que o Sistema Usa para Representar Tempo"
		nature:     "theoretical"
		role:       "framework"
		definition: "Tempo em sistemas financeiros requer tipos distintos para conceitos distintos. Usar o tipo errado para o conceito errado causa bugs sutis que se manifestam como erros financeiros. Conceito de 'temporal type discipline' (2024+): usar tipo correto para conceito correto, sem exceção: **(1) Instant** — ponto exato no tempo, independente de timezone. Representação: UTC timestamp (ISO 8601: 2026-03-13T14:30:00Z). Uso: quando evento aconteceu (created_at, approved_at, settled_at, signed_at). Propriedade: mesmo momento = mesmo valor em qualquer timezone (14:30 UTC é 14:30 UTC em São Paulo, Tokyo, New York). Armazenamento: TIMESTAMPTZ em PostgreSQL (armazena em UTC, converte per session timezone — mas backend DEVE operar em UTC). **(2) LocalDate** — data sem hora e sem timezone. Representação: yyyy-mm-dd (2026-03-13). Uso: datas de negócio onde o conceito é 'qual dia' independente de momento ou timezone. Vencimento (NF vence em 25/03/2026 — vence no dia, não num instante), data de emissão, data de safra, data de corte de reporting. Propriedade: 2026-03-25 é 25 de março em QUALQUER timezone. Armazenamento: DATE em PostgreSQL (sem hora, sem timezone). **(3) LocalDateTime** — data + hora sem timezone. Raro em sistemas financeiros (a maioria é Instant ou LocalDate). Uso: quando é necessário representar 'dia e hora' sem vincular a timezone (e.g., horário de corte '15:00' como configuração — é 15:00 no timezone de negócio, não um instante). **(4) BusinessDate** — data de negócio que considera calendário de feriados e horário de corte. Não é um tipo primitivo de linguagem — é um conceito derivado. Representação: LocalDate + contexto de calendário (country, holidays). Uso: settlement date (D+1 business day), deadline de reporting (5th business day), document expiry (30 business days from issue). Derivado: de um Instant (momento da aprovação) via timezone conversion + cutoff check + business day addition. Conceito de 'vencimento ≠ timestamp' (2024+): esta é a distinção mais crítica. 'Esta NF vence em 25/03/2026' é LocalDate — não tem hora, não tem timezone. Vence no dia 25, independente de em qual timezone você está. 'Esta operação foi aprovada às 14:30 UTC' é Instant — momento exato no tempo, representável em qualquer timezone. Misturar: armazenar vencimento como TIMESTAMPTZ com hora 00:00:00 UTC → quando exibido em America/Sao_Paulo (UTC-3): mostra 24/03/2026 21:00 — vencimento MUDOU DE DIA! Porque midnight UTC = 9pm do dia anterior em BRT. Armazenar approval como DATE sem hora → perde informação de quando no dia ocorreu (2 approvals no mesmo dia: qual foi primeiro? Impossível saber sem hora). Conceito de 'temporal type as semantic commitment' (2024+): o tipo escolhido COMUNICA o significado. TIMESTAMPTZ = 'este campo é um momento no tempo.' DATE = 'este campo é um dia de negócio.' Tipo errado = semântica errada = bugs."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, temporal types mapping completo: **Instants (TIMESTAMPTZ — 'quando aconteceu'):** operation.created_at — momento exato da criação. operation.approved_at — momento da aprovação pela construtora. operation.cessao_signed_at — momento da assinatura do instrumento de cessão. operation.settled_at — momento da confirmação de liquidação pelo banco. operation.paid_at — momento do pagamento pelo sacado no vencimento. score.calculated_at — momento do cálculo do score. document.uploaded_at — momento do upload. contract.signed_at — momento da assinatura digital. audit_entry.timestamp — momento do evento de auditoria. Todos: UTC. Todos: momento exato. **LocalDates (DATE — 'qual dia'):** receivable.maturity_date — vencimento da NF (dia, sem hora). receivable.issue_date — data de emissão da NF (dia). operation.settlement_date — data alvo de liquidação (business date calculada). operation.vintage — mês de originação (derivado de created_at convertido para BRT). report.period_start / period_end — período de reporting. compliance.document_expiry_date — validade do documento de compliance. Todos: sem hora, sem timezone. Conceito: 'vence no dia' ou 'emitido no dia.' **BusinessDates (derivados — 'qual dia útil'):** operation.settlement_date = businessCalendar.addBusinessDays(operation.approved_at.toLocalDate('America/Sao_Paulo'), 1, 'BR'). Derivação: Instant (approval moment) → convert to LocalDate in business timezone → add business days using calendar → LocalDate result. **Não usados:** LocalDateTime para campos financeiros (sem timezone = ambíguo). Duration sem qualificador (30 dias = calendar ou business? Sempre explícito: '30 calendar days' ou '30 business days'). String para datas (NEVER — formatted string é ambíguo e não-calculável)."
		meshImplication: "Temporal type implementation rules: (1) **type mapping document** — mesh-spec /foundations/temporal-types.md: para cada campo temporal no sistema: nome, tipo (Instant/LocalDate/BusinessDate), storage type (TIMESTAMPTZ/DATE), format em API (ISO 8601), justificativa. Agente consulta antes de criar novo campo temporal. (2) **no stringly-typed dates** — NEVER store date as VARCHAR. NEVER store timestamp as VARCHAR. NEVER store formatted date ('25/03/2026') in database. Types: enforced by database schema (TIMESTAMPTZ, DATE) + application types (Kotlin: Instant, LocalDate; Python: datetime, date). String: ONLY for serialization (API response JSON, log message). Internal: always typed. (3) **vencimento = DATE, always** — every maturity_date, due_date, expiry_date, issue_date: DATE type in PostgreSQL. No hora. No timezone. If developer creates maturity_at TIMESTAMPTZ: flag in code review — 'maturity is a date concept, not a timestamp. Use DATE. See /foundations/temporal-types.md.' (4) **events = TIMESTAMPTZ, always** — every created_at, approved_at, signed_at, settled_at: TIMESTAMPTZ in UTC. Moment in time. Orderable (which happened first?). Timezone-convertible for display. (5) **API serialization** — Instants: '2026-03-13T14:30:00Z' (ISO 8601 with Z suffix for UTC). ALWAYS with Z. Not: '2026-03-13T14:30:00' (no timezone = ambiguous). Not: '2026-03-13T14:30:00-03:00' (BRT offset — valid but backend should standardize on Z/UTC). LocalDates: '2026-03-13' (ISO 8601 date only). Not: '13/03/2026' (locale-specific formatting — formatting is presentation layer per IL lens). (6) **CLAUDE.md** — 'temporal fields: Instant (TIMESTAMPTZ UTC) for events/actions/moments. LocalDate (DATE) for business dates (vencimento, emissão, validade, safra). NEVER VARCHAR for dates. NEVER TIMESTAMPTZ for vencimento (day shifts with timezone!). API: ISO 8601 always (Instant with Z, LocalDate as yyyy-mm-dd).' Anti-pattern: maturity_date TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT '2026-03-25 00:00:00+00:00'. PostgreSQL stores correctly. Application reads in UTC: March 25 00:00 UTC. Display in America/Sao_Paulo (UTC-3): March 24 21:00. Vencimento que era dia 25 agora aparece como dia 24. Fornecedor vê: 'vence 24/03.' Construtora vê (in different display timezone, e.g., UTC): 'vence 25/03.' Dois participantes da mesma operação veem vencimentos diferentes. Porque: vencimento stored as timestamp when it should be date."
		rationale: "Temporal type discipline 2024+. Vencimento ≠ timestamp 2024+. Temporal type as semantic commitment 2024+. Na Mesh, Instant para eventos (momento exato), LocalDate para business dates (qual dia). Wrong type: vencimento changes day when timezone applied. Correct type: vencimento is 2026-03-25 in every timezone, every display, every participant."
	},
	{
		id:         "tm-settlement-windows"
		name:       "Janelas de Liquidação: D+N com Business Days, Cutoffs e Timezone"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "quarterly"
		definition: "Settlement window é o período entre operação aprovada e liquidação (pagamento ao cedente). D+1 = 1 business day after approval. Mas: 'after approval' depende de QUANDO no dia a aprovação ocorreu (antes ou depois do cutoff) e de QUAL timezone define 'dia.' Conceito de 'settlement calculation chain' (2024+): settlement date é resultado de uma chain de transformações onde cada step deve ser correto — erro em qualquer step = settlement date errada: (1) **event moment** — Instant when operation was approved. Ex: 2026-03-13T20:30:00Z (UTC). (2) **timezone conversion** — convert Instant to business timezone. America/Sao_Paulo: 2026-03-13T17:30:00 BRT. O momento é o mesmo; a representação local determina 'qual dia' e 'que horas' no contexto de negócio. (3) **cutoff check** — compare local time with daily cutoff. Se cutoff é 15:00 BRT: 17:30 > 15:00 → approval counts for NEXT business day (not today — too late for today's bank batch). Se approval era 14:30 BRT < 15:00: counts for today. Cutoff: determina o 'dia base' para D+N calculation. (4) **base date determination** — if before cutoff: base = today (approval day). If after cutoff: base = next business day. In our example: 17:30 > 15:00 cutoff → base = next BD after 2026-03-13. If 2026-03-13 is Friday: next BD = Monday 2026-03-16. (5) **business day addition** — addBusinessDays(base_date, N, country) using BusinessCalendar (IL lens). D+1 from base 2026-03-16 (Monday, no holidays): settlement = 2026-03-17 (Tuesday). D+1 from base 2026-03-13 (Thursday, before holiday Friday): settlement = Monday 2026-03-16 (skips Friday holiday). (6) **settlement date** — LocalDate result. This is when bank transfer instruction should be executed. Conceito de 'cutoff time' (2024+): daily operational boundary that determines which business day an operation 'belongs to.' Cutoffs exist because bank payment systems have daily processing cycles. If bank's batch runs at 16:00: operations approved after 16:00 cannot make today's batch → settled in tomorrow's batch → effective D+1 from tomorrow, not from today. Mesh cutoff MUST align with (or precede) bank's processing schedule. If Mesh cutoff is 15:00 and bank batch is 16:00: 1 hour buffer for Mesh to compile batch and send instructions. If Mesh cutoff is 16:30 and bank batch is 16:00: operations approved 16:00-16:30 miss bank batch despite being 'today' per Mesh."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, settlement calculation with detailed examples: **Configuration:** cutoff_time = 15:00 BRT (America/Sao_Paulo). Settlement cycle = D+1 business day. Bank batch time = 16:00 BRT. Buffer: 1 hour (cutoff to bank batch). **Example 1 — normal (before cutoff, weekday):** approval: 2026-03-12T13:30:00Z = 10:30 BRT (Thursday). 10:30 < 15:00 cutoff → base_date = 2026-03-12 (Thursday). Settlement: addBusinessDays(2026-03-12, 1, 'BR') = 2026-03-13 (Friday, assuming no holiday). Fornecedor recebe: sexta-feira. Display at approval: 'Depósito previsto: 13/03/2026 (sexta-feira).' **Example 2 — after cutoff:** approval: 2026-03-12T19:00:00Z = 16:00 BRT (Thursday). 16:00 ≥ 15:00 cutoff → base_date deferred. Next BD after Thursday = Friday 2026-03-13. Settlement: addBusinessDays(2026-03-13, 1, 'BR') = 2026-03-14 (Saturday? No — Saturday is not BD). Actually: Friday + 1 BD = Monday 2026-03-16. Fornecedor recebe: segunda-feira. Display: 'Aprovação após horário de corte (15:00). Depósito previsto: 16/03/2026 (segunda-feira).' **Example 3 — Friday afternoon before cutoff:** approval: 2026-03-13T17:00:00Z = 14:00 BRT (Friday). 14:00 < 15:00 → base_date = 2026-03-13 (Friday). Settlement: addBusinessDays(2026-03-13, 1, 'BR') = 2026-03-16 (Monday — skips weekend). Fornecedor recebe: segunda. **Example 4 — before holiday:** approval: 2026-04-17T16:00:00Z = 13:00 BRT (Thursday). 13:00 < 15:00 → base_date = 2026-04-17 (Thursday). April 18 is Friday (business day? Check calendar). April 21 = Tiradentes (Monday holiday). Settlement: addBusinessDays(2026-04-17, 1, 'BR') = 2026-04-18 (Friday — if not holiday). Fornecedor recebe: sexta. **Example 5 — edge: exactly at cutoff:** approval at exactly 15:00:00 BRT. Rule: cutoff is exclusive (< 15:00 = today, ≥ 15:00 = tomorrow). 15:00:00 = tomorrow. Documented in mesh-spec. Tested: property test verifies boundary."
		meshImplication: "Settlement implementation: (1) **settlement calculator function** — calculateSettlementDate(approvalInstant: Instant, timezone: ZoneId, cutoffTime: LocalTime, settlementDays: Int, country: CountryCode): LocalDate. Steps: (a) convert Instant to ZonedDateTime in timezone. (b) extract LocalTime. (c) if localTime < cutoff: baseDate = localDate. Else: baseDate = businessCalendar.nextBusinessDay(localDate, country). (d) return businessCalendar.addBusinessDays(baseDate, settlementDays, country). Pure function. Deterministic. Same inputs → same output always. No side effects. Testable. (2) **cutoff as configuration** — per banking partner: cutoff may differ. Config: { partner_id: 'bankX', cutoff_time: '15:00', cutoff_timezone: 'America/Sao_Paulo', batch_time: '16:00' }. If multiple banking partners: cutoff = EARLIEST (most conservative — ensures all partners receive instructions on time). Config: changeable without code deploy. (3) **settlement date shown to fornecedor** — at submission (pre-approval): 'estimativa de depósito: [estimated_date]' (calculated assuming approval today before cutoff). At approval: 'depósito previsto: [settlement_date]' (calculated with actual approval time). If approval after cutoff: 'Aprovação após horário de corte. Depósito previsto: [date].' Transparent: fornecedor understands why date is what it is. (4) **settlement date vs actual settlement** — settlement_date (LocalDate): target. Calculated at approval. actual_settlement_date (LocalDate): when bank confirmed transfer. If actual > target: SLA violation (CL lens). Monitor: delta = countBusinessDays(settlement_date, actual_settlement_date). Alert if delta > 0 (any late settlement). (5) **batch settlement process** — daily: at cutoff + buffer (15:30 BRT): collect all operations with settlement_date = today (or tomorrow, depending on when batch is sent) that haven't been sent to bank. Generate: bank instruction file or API call with payment details. Send: to banking partner. Log: batch_id, operation_ids, total_amount, sent_at. (6) **cutoff boundary rule** — documented: '≥ cutoff = next day.' Not '> cutoff' (ambiguous at exactly cutoff time). Property test: for approval at cutoff-1ms → today. For approval at cutoff → tomorrow. For approval at cutoff+1ms → tomorrow. Boundary: explicit, documented, tested. (7) **CLAUDE.md** — 'settlement date: ALWAYS use calculateSettlementDate(). Never: approvalDate.plusDays(1). Never: manual business day calculation. Cutoff: from configuration. Business days: from BusinessCalendar. Show settlement date to fornecedor at approval.' Anti-pattern: settlement = approval_date + 1 calendar day. Friday 14:00 approval + 1 = Saturday. Bank: closed. Payment instruction: rejected. Fornecedor: expects Saturday (system showed), receives Monday. Or: no cutoff — approval at 23:59 BRT included in 'today' batch. Bank batch ran at 16:00. Instruction: arrives for next day's batch. System: says D+1 from today. Reality: D+1 from tomorrow = D+2 effective."
		dependsOn: ["tm-temporal-primitives"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-internationalization-and-localization-architecture"
			conceptId: "il-business-calendar-abstraction"
			context:   "IL defines BusinessCalendar as service: addBusinessDays(date, N, country) with holidays per country. TM settlement windows CONSUMES BusinessCalendar: calculateSettlementDate uses addBusinessDays internally for the D+N calculation. IL provides the calendar infrastructure (which days are holidays, which are weekends); TM provides the settlement-specific logic (Instant → timezone conversion → cutoff check → calendar query → settlement date). IL is the temporal foundation; TM is the financial application built on it."
		}]
		rationale: "Settlement calculation chain 2024+. Cutoff time 2024+. Na Mesh, settlement = chain: timezone conversion → cutoff check → business day addition. Each step must be correct. Skip timezone: wrong day. Skip cutoff: wrong base. Skip calendar: weekend/holiday. Wrong settlement date: fornecedor doesn't receive when expected → trust erosion + SLA violation."
	},
	{
		id:         "tm-bitemporal-modeling"
		name:       "Modelagem Bitemporal: Quando Aconteceu vs Quando Soubemos"
		nature:     "theoretical"
		role:       "framework"
		reviewCadence: "annual"
		definition: "Snodgrass (2000, Developing Time-Oriented Database Applications): bitemporal modeling tracks 2 independent time dimensions: **(1) valid time (when-happened)** — when the fact was true in the real world. 'NF foi emitida em 01/03/2026.' 'Compliance do fornecedor expirou em 28/02/2026.' 'Sacado defaultou em 15/04/2026.' Valid time: about the WORLD, not about the SYSTEM. (2) **transaction time (when-known)** — when the system RECORDED the fact. 'Descobrimos em 05/03/2026 que NF foi emitida em 01/03/2026' (late-arriving data — 4 days between event and recording). 'Descobrimos em 15/03/2026 que compliance tinha expirado em 28/02/2026' (retroactive discovery — system didn't know until 15 days after). Transaction time: about the SYSTEM, not about the WORLD. Why it matters in financial systems: (a) **late-arriving data** — data arrives after the fact. NF emitida March 1, uploaded March 5. Score calculated March 3 (before NF was known) didn't include this NF's data. Was score correct at time of calculation? Yes (based on data available then). Is it correct now with new data? Maybe not. Bitemporal: both states preserved. (b) **corrections** — score was 65 on March 5 (based on data available). On March 10, data correction (e.g., previous default discovered): score recalculated = 58. Without bitemporal: score is 58 now, no record of 65 ever existing. With bitemporal: score was 65 (valid March 5-10), corrected to 58 (valid from March 10). Both facts preserved. If operation was approved at score 65 on March 7: approval was correct at the time. (c) **regulatory audit** — regulador (CVM, Bacen) asks: 'O que vocês sabiam em 5 de março quando aprovaram esta operação?' Without bitemporal: system shows current state (includes all corrections since March 5 — misleading). With bitemporal: system reconstructs exact state AS-OF March 5 — what the system knew at that moment. Defensible: 'on March 5, we knew score was 65, compliance was ok, and we approved. The correction to 58 came on March 10, after approval.' Conceito de 'as-of query' (Snodgrass): query que responde: 'qual era o estado desta entidade as-of [valid_time] segundo o que sabíamos as-of [transaction_time]?' Essential for: audit, regulatory compliance, dispute resolution (CL lens dossier), model calibration (TV lens backtesting)."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, bitemporal applications concretas: **(1) Score history (primary use case):** Score calculated March 5 for operation #1234 = 65 (based on: payment history ok, compliance ok, 3 months of data). On March 10: new data arrives (previous default by this sacado with another FIDC, not previously known). Score recalculated = 58. Bitemporal records: {operation_id: 1234, score: 65, valid_from: 2026-03-05, valid_to: 2026-03-10, recorded_at: 2026-03-05, model_version: 'v2.3', features_snapshot: {...}}. {operation_id: 1234, score: 58, valid_from: 2026-03-10, valid_to: null (current), recorded_at: 2026-03-10, model_version: 'v2.3', features_snapshot: {...}, correction_reason: 'new default data for sacado discovered'}. As-of queries: 'score as-of March 7' → 65 (what we knew then — correction hadn't happened). 'Score as-of March 12' → 58 (after correction). 'Score at time of approval (March 7)' → 65 (this is what informed the approval decision). **(2) Compliance status history:** Fornecedor compliance was 'ok' on Feb 15 (all documents valid, recorded Feb 15). On March 1, system discovers: certidão negativa actually expired on Feb 28 (document has 180-day validity, but expiry date was miscalculated or document was replaced by expired version). Bitemporal: {supplier_id: ABC, status: 'compliant', valid_from: 2026-02-15, valid_to: 2026-02-28, recorded_at: 2026-02-15}. {supplier_id: ABC, status: 'non_compliant', valid_from: 2026-02-28, valid_to: null, recorded_at: 2026-03-01, reason: 'certidao_negativa expired'}. As-of queries: 'compliance as-of Feb 25, knowledge as-of Feb 20' → compliant (didn't know about expiry). 'Compliance as-of Feb 25, knowledge as-of March 2' → non-compliant since Feb 28 (now we know). **(3) Regulatory audit scenario:** CVM asks about operation #1234 approved on Feb 25: 'was the fornecedor compliant when you approved?' Query: compliance where valid_time includes Feb 25 AND transaction_time ≤ Feb 25. Result: 'status was compliant — we didn't know about the upcoming expiry.' Defensible: decision was correct based on information available at decision time."
		meshImplication: "Bitemporal implementation: (1) **not for everything — selective application.** Full bitemporal is complex (2 time dimensions × every table = significant schema and query complexity). Apply WHERE audit/regulatory REQUIRES temporal reconstruction: scores (what score at approval time?), compliance status (was supplier compliant at approval?), operation state (what was state when decision was made?), and potentially: model parameters (which model version with which thresholds was active?). NOT for: UI preferences, org settings (unless audit-relevant), configuration, temporary data. (2) **event sourcing as bitemporal foundation** — event sourced systems NATURALLY preserve transaction time: each event has timestamp = when it was recorded. Replay events up to timestamp T: reconstructs system state as-of T (from transaction time perspective). This gives ~80% of bitemporal benefit with zero additional schema complexity. Add valid_time to events for full bitemporal: each event carries 'this happened in the world at [valid_time]' in addition to 'we recorded this at [event.timestamp/transaction_time].' (3) **score versioning (concrete implementation)** — each score calculation: stored as immutable record with: {score_id, operation_id, score_value, model_version, calculated_at (transaction time), valid_from (when score applies — usually same as calculated_at unless backdated), features_snapshot (frozen copy of features used), correction_reason (null if original, text if correction)}. When score is recalculated (correction, new data): NEW record created. Old: valid_to set to now. Query 'score at approval time': WHERE valid_from ≤ approval_date AND (valid_to IS NULL OR valid_to > approval_date) AND recorded_at ≤ approval_date. Returns: the score that was known and valid when approval happened. (4) **compliance snapshots** — periodic or event-driven snapshots of compliance status per supplier. Each snapshot: {supplier_id, status, documents_status: [{doc_type, valid, expiry_date}], snapshot_at (transaction time), valid_as_of (valid time)}. If compliance changes retroactively (expired document discovered late): new snapshot with valid_as_of = actual expiry date, recorded_at = now. Old snapshot: preserved (shows what we believed). (5) **simplified approach for MVP** — full bitemporal with separate valid_time and transaction_time columns: complex. MVP: event sourcing (gives transaction time built-in) + immutable records (never overwrite, always append correction as new record). This gives: ability to reconstruct state at any transaction time (replay events). Plus: correction records preserve both old and new values. ~80% of bitemporal benefit. Full bitemporal with explicit valid_time: add when FIDC regulatory audit DEMANDS as-of queries that distinguish 'when it happened' from 'when we knew' (post-FIDC-launch). (6) **CLAUDE.md** — 'scores and compliance status: NEVER overwrite — always append new record with timestamp and preserve old. If correcting: create new record with correction_reason, link to original, preserve original unchanged. Event sourcing: every state change is an immutable event with timestamp. For regulatory questions: system must be able to answer: what did we know, when?'"
		dependsOn: ["tm-temporal-primitives"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-event-driven-architecture-patterns"
			conceptId: "eda-event-sourcing"
			context:   "EDA event sourcing preserves every state change as immutable event with timestamp — this IS transaction time naturally. TM bitemporal adds valid time: when did the fact actually happen in the real world (which may differ from when we recorded it). EDA gives 'what happened in the system, when (transaction time).' TM adds 'what happened in reality, when (valid time) — and when did we learn about it (transaction time).' EDA is the foundation; TM is the temporal enrichment for financial audit and compliance."
		}]
		rationale: "Snodgrass 2000: bitemporal modeling. As-of query. Na Mesh, bitemporal for scores and compliance: regulador asks 'what did you know on Feb 25?' — system answers with exact state at that moment, distinguishing current knowledge from knowledge-at-the-time. Without bitemporal: only current state (includes corrections). With: historical state as-known-at-time. Defensible in regulatory audit."
