	{
		id:         "tm-day-count-and-accrual"
		name:       "Contagem de Dias e Accrual: Como Tempo Se Converte em Dinheiro"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "property"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Em operações financeiras, tempo é dinheiro — literalmente. Taxa de antecipação é função do prazo: mais dias até vencimento = maior deságio (fornecedor 'paga' mais para receber mais cedo). A forma de contar esses dias afeta o valor em reais. Conceito de 'day count convention' (ISDA — International Swaps and Derivatives Association — standards, widely used in Brazilian financial market): como contar dias entre duas datas para cálculo financeiro. Convenções principais: **(1) actual/360** — dias REAIS (calendário) entre datas ÷ ano de 360 dias. Usado em: mercado interbancário brasileiro (operações de CDI), operações de crédito bancário. Cálculo: taxa_periodo = taxa_anual × actual_days / 360. Linear. **(2) actual/365** — dias reais ÷ ano de 365 dias. Usado em: alguns instrumentos de renda fixa. Similar a actual/360 mas com denominador 365. **(3) business/252** — dias ÚTEIS entre datas ÷ ano de 252 dias úteis. Usado em: mercado brasileiro para derivativos, CDI acumulado, operações indexadas a CDI, FIDC. Cálculo: taxa_periodo = (1 + taxa_anual)^(business_days/252) - 1. Exponencial (capitalização composta). Este é o padrão para antecipação de recebíveis via FIDC. **(4) 30/360** — assume meses de 30 dias ÷ ano 360. Usado em: bonds americanos. Menos comum no Brasil. Conceito de 'day count matters for pricing — real money' (2024+): para antecipação com taxa de 2,5% a.m. (CDI + spread): se prazo calculado como 30 calendar days (actual/360): deságio = X. Se prazo calculado como 22 business days (business/252): deságio = Y ≠ X. A diferença: dinheiro real. R$15 por operação de R$50k × 1.000 ops/mês = R$15.000/mês dependendo da convenção. Convention DEVE ser: (a) definida explicitamente no contrato de cessão e no regulamento do FIDC (CL lens: contract-code alignment). (b) implementada consistentemente no código (uma única função de cálculo, não N implementações ad hoc). (c) testada com edge cases (meses com 28/29/30/31 dias, meses com muitos feriados como fevereiro com Carnaval, dezembro com Natal)."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, day count: **Convention padrão: business/252 (dias úteis / 252).** Razão: padrão do mercado financeiro brasileiro para operações indexadas a CDI, que é a base de precificação de FIDCs. Regulamento do FIDC: especifica convention. Mesh: implementa per regulamento. Default: business/252. **Cálculo detalhado:** (1) prazo_du = businessCalendar.countBusinessDays(settlement_date, maturity_date, 'BR'). Se settlement 14/03/2026 (sexta) e maturity 13/04/2026 (segunda): calendar days = 30. Business days = ~22 (depende de feriados no período — Semana Santa pode estar neste range). (2) taxa_periodo = (1 + taxa_anual)^(prazo_du / 252) - 1. Se taxa_anual = 13,75% (CDI + spread): taxa_periodo = (1,1375)^(22/252) - 1 ≈ 0,01123 = 1,123%. (3) deságio = valor_face × taxa_periodo = R$50.000 × 0,01123 = R$561,50. (4) valor_liquido = valor_face - deságio = R$50.000 - R$561,50 = R$49.438,50. **Comparação com actual/360:** taxa_periodo = 0,1375 × 30/360 = 0,01146 = 1,146%. deságio = R$50.000 × 0,01146 = R$573,00. Diferença: R$573 - R$561,50 = R$11,50 por operação. × 1.000 ops/mês = R$11.500/mês. R$138.000/ano. **Quem perde com convention errada:** se sistema usa actual/360 mas contrato diz business/252: fornecedor paga R$11,50 a mais por operação. Se 1.000 fornecedores × 5 ops/mês: R$57.500/mês overpaying. Se descoberto: Mesh em breach de contrato. Restitution: potentially millions."
		meshImplication: "Day count implementation: (1) **DayCountConvention as configuration** — enum: BUSINESS_252, ACTUAL_360, ACTUAL_365, THIRTY_360. Default for Mesh Brazil: BUSINESS_252. Configurable per FIDC (each FIDC's regulamento may specify different convention). If FIDC A uses business/252 and FIDC B uses actual/360: system supports both, per-FIDC config. (2) **countBusinessDays function** — uses BusinessCalendar (IL lens). countBusinessDays(start: LocalDate, end: LocalDate, country: CountryCode): Int. Counts days that are NOT weekend AND NOT holiday between start and end (exclusive of start, inclusive of end — convention may vary; document explicitly). Tested: for every pair of dates in test range. Verified: against Banco Central's published business day calendar. (3) **pricing function** — calculateDiscount(faceValue: Money, annualRate: Decimal, startDate: LocalDate, endDate: LocalDate, convention: DayCountConvention, country: CountryCode): Money. Pure function. Deterministic. Same inputs → same output every time. Implementation per convention: BUSINESS_252: discount = faceValue × ((1 + rate)^(businessDays/252) - 1). ACTUAL_360: discount = faceValue × (rate × calendarDays / 360). Etc. (4) **contract alignment — CRITICAL** — contrato de cessão (CL lens) especifica: 'deságio calculado pelo método de [dias úteis/252], conforme calendário de feriados nacionais publicado pelo Banco Central do Brasil.' Convention in contract AND convention in code MUST match. If mismatch: Mesh in breach. Verification: part of quarterly contract-code alignment audit (CL lens cl-contract-review). (5) **pro-rata for partial periods** — if operation settled mid-month or period: deságio pro-rata by actual business days remaining. Not rounded to full month. Exact: businessCalendar.countBusinessDays(settlementDate, maturityDate, 'BR'). (6) **display to fornecedor — transparent** — 'Prazo: 22 dias úteis. Taxa anual: 13,75%. Taxa do período: 1,12%. Deságio: R$561,50. Valor líquido: R$49.438,50. Método: dias úteis/252.' Transparent: fornecedor can independently verify with calendar + calculator. If opaque ('deságio: R$561,50' without formula): distrust ('how did they calculate this?'). Transparency: builds trust (TC lens). (7) **testing** — property-based test (TV lens): for any (faceValue, rate, start, end, convention): (a) discount ≥ 0. (b) discount < faceValue. (c) longer period → higher discount (monotonicity). (d) discount is consistent with convention formula. Edge cases: months with 20 vs 23 business days. February (28/29 days). December (holidays). Carnaval (multiple consecutive holidays reducing business days). Year crossing. (8) **CLAUDE.md** — 'pricing/deságio: use calculateDiscount() with configured DayCountConvention. Default: BUSINESS_252. NEVER hardcode day count formula inline. NEVER use calendar days when convention is business days. Convention in code MUST match convention in contract. When implementing new pricing logic: verify convention with /legal/contract-code-alignment.md.' Anti-pattern: calculating deságio with 30 calendar days (actual/360) when contract says 22 business days (business/252). 8 extra days × rate = fornecedor pays more than contracted. × 1.000 ops = R$11.500/mês overcharging. If discovered: breach + restitution + trust destruction + regulatory scrutiny."
		dependsOn: ["tm-temporal-primitives", "tm-settlement-windows"]
		rationale: "Day count conventions ISDA. business/252 is Brazilian standard for CDI-linked operations. Na Mesh, R$11,50 per operation difference between conventions × 1.000 ops = R$11.500/mês. Convention MUST: be explicit in contract, implemented correctly in code, tested for edge cases, and displayed transparently to fornecedor. Mismatch: breach of contract + financial damage."
	},
	{
		id:         "tm-cutoff-and-batch-cycles"
		name:       "Cutoffs e Ciclos de Batch: Fronteiras Temporais que Governam Processamento"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "quarterly"
		definition: "Financial systems operate in cycles bounded by temporal cutoffs. Conceito de 'operational time boundaries' (2024+): **(1) daily cutoff** — time after which new operations are deferred to next business day. Before cutoff: 'today.' After: 'tomorrow.' Determines: which operations are in today's settlement batch. **(2) batch processing window** — period when batch jobs run: settlement instructions sent to bank, reconciliation run, reports generated. Typically: after daily cutoff, before next business day opens. **(3) reporting period** — boundaries for reports: monthly (1st to last calendar day), weekly, daily. Period closure: all operations finalized, numbers 'locked,' no further modifications to closed period. **(4) regulatory deadlines** — reporting to regulador by Nth business day. CVM: mensal FIDC report by 5th BD. Bacen: daily settlement report (if applicable). Conceito de 'period immutability' (2024+): closed period CANNOT be retroactively modified. Accounting principle: once books are closed, corrections go to current period with reference to original. If operation from March is discovered in April to have error: correction entry in APRIL, referencing March operation. March's numbers: unchanged. This prevents: historical report that shows different numbers each time it's generated (unreliable), and regulatory submissions that don't match previously submitted data. Conceito de 'late-arriving operations' (2024+): operation approved after cutoff or after period close. Policy must be explicit: (a) after daily cutoff: defer to next business day (standard). (b) after monthly period close: include in current period if within grace window, or defer to next period."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, temporal boundaries: **(1) Daily settlement cutoff: 15:00 BRT.** Operations approved before 15:00: included in today's settlement batch. After: deferred to next BD's batch. Bank instruction: compiled at 15:30 BRT (30 min buffer after cutoff to aggregate + validate + send). Bank processing: same day or overnight (depends on bank partner schedule). (2) **Daily reconciliation: 06:00 BRT.** Every morning: system reconciles yesterday's bank statement with internal records. Discrepancies: flagged before business day starts. Operations team: sees reconciliation status at 07:00 when day starts. (3) **Monthly reporting period: 1st to last calendar day.** Close: 3rd business day of following month (allow for late-arriving bank confirmations, corrections). During close: numbers are provisional (may change with late data). After close: numbers are FINAL. Corrections: in next month's report as adjustment entry referencing original period. FIDC reporting: generated from closed period data. (4) **FIDC reporting deadline: CVM mensal by 5th BD.** System: auto-generates draft report by 3rd BD. FIDC gestor: reviews by 4th BD. Submit: by 5th BD. Buffer: 2 BD for review between generation and deadline."
		meshImplication: "Cutoff implementation: (1) **cutoff as configuration** — { daily_settlement_cutoff: '15:00', timezone: 'America/Sao_Paulo', bank_batch_time: '16:00', reconciliation_time: '06:00', monthly_close_deadline_bd: 3 }. Per banking partner: cutoff may differ. Changeable: without code deploy. (2) **cutoff enforcement in settlement calculator** — calculateSettlementDate: compares approval time vs cutoff. After: defers base date. This is WHERE cutoff logic lives — in 1 function, not scattered. Every settlement calculation: goes through this function. (3) **batch job scheduling** — settlement batch: triggered at configured time (15:30 BRT). Collects: all operations with settlement_date ≤ today that haven't been sent to bank. Generates: bank instruction (file or API call). Sends. Logs: {batch_id, operation_count, total_amount, sent_at, bank_partner}. If batch fails: alert + retry. If retry fails: manual intervention (operations settle D+1 instead of D+0). (4) **period close process** — monthly close: automated job on 3rd BD of following month. Steps: (a) verify: all operations in period are in terminal state (settled, cancelled — not pending). If pending: flag for resolution or force-defer to next period. (b) run reconciliation for entire period: all ledger entries balance? All bank statements matched? (c) generate period summary: volume, amounts, fees, defaults, scoring accuracy. (d) mark period as 'CLOSED.' (e) lock: no modifications to records with dates in closed period. Corrections: new entries in current period with reference. (5) **late-arriving data** — operation approved 1 minute after cutoff: deferred (standard, no exception — cutoff is cutoff). Bank confirmation arriving after period close: (a) if within grace window (close + 1 BD): included in period. (b) if after grace: adjustment in current period. (6) **immutability of closed periods** — NEVER retroactively modify closed period data. Not: 'oops, forgot this operation — let me add it to March.' Yes: 'adjustment in April: operation from March discovered, valued at R$X.' March report: unchanged. April report: shows adjustment. Total: correct. History: auditable. (7) **CLAUDE.md** — 'cutoff times: use configured values, never hardcode. Settlement batch: after cutoff. Period close: immutable after finalization — corrections in current period with reference. Late data: defer, never backdate into closed period.' Anti-pattern: no period close — monthly report generated on-the-fly each time. Report generated March 5: shows 147 operations. Report generated March 15: shows 149 (2 late confirmations). Same period: different numbers depending on when you look. CVM submission on March 5: 147. Audit in June: sees 149. Discrepancy. With period close: March report is ALWAYS 147 (closed). Late confirmations: April adjustment."
		dependsOn: ["tm-temporal-primitives", "tm-settlement-windows"]
		rationale: "Operational time boundaries 2024+. Period immutability 2024+. Late-arriving operations 2024+. Na Mesh, cutoff at 15:00 BRT: clear temporal boundary. Period close on 3rd BD: numbers locked. Corrections: in current period. These boundaries prevent: phantom settlements (operation in wrong day's batch), reconciliation mismatches (numbers change after close), and regulatory discrepancies (submitted data differs from audited data)."
	},
	{
		id:         "tm-timezone-discipline"
		name:       "Disciplina de Timezone: UTC Everywhere, Local Time Only in Presentation"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "property"
		reviewCadence: "annual"
		definition: "Timezone errors are subtle and devastating in financial systems. A clock that's wrong by 3 hours (UTC vs BRT) can shift a settlement to the wrong day, assign an operation to the wrong vintage month, or calculate the wrong number of business days. Conceito de 'UTC as single source of temporal truth' (2024+): ALL timestamps stored in UTC. ALL temporal calculations performed in UTC (or with EXPLICIT timezone conversion at defined points). Local time: ONLY in presentation layer (UI, notifications, reports displayed to humans). Never in storage. Never in business logic (except at defined conversion points). Concepto de 'timezone conversion points' (2024+): in the system, there are EXACTLY 3 points where timezone matters — everywhere else is UTC: **(1) input** — user performs action at their local time. Frontend: captures local time. Backend: immediately converts to UTC. Stored: UTC. The local time of the user's action: irrelevant to the system (what matters is the UTC instant). **(2) business logic** — specific calculations require business timezone: cutoff check (is this before 15:00 BRT?), vintage assignment (which BRT month?), business date derivation (which BRT date for settlement?). At these points: Instant.atZone('America/Sao_Paulo') → local time → compare/extract → back to UTC or LocalDate. Conversion: EXPLICIT, with named timezone (ZoneId.of('America/Sao_Paulo')), never implicit system default. **(3) output** — display to user. Dashboard shows: '13/03/2026 14:30' (BRT, user's timezone). Notification: 'Operação aprovada às 14:30.' Report: dates in BRT. At this point: UTC → user's timezone for display. Everywhere else: UTC. No ambiguity. No deployment-dependent behavior."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, timezone implementation: **Storage:** all TIMESTAMPTZ columns store UTC internally. PostgreSQL: SET timezone = 'UTC' for all application connections (explicit). Column: TIMESTAMPTZ ensures timezone-awareness. **Business timezone:** America/Sao_Paulo (BRT, UTC-3). Note: Brazil abolished DST in 2019 (Decreto 9.772/2019), so BRT is consistently UTC-3. But: (a) America/Sao_Paulo zone in tz database still has historical DST entries (for pre-2019 data). (b) if Mesh expands to countries WITH DST (Colombia doesn't have, but Chile does): timezone library handles automatically. Rule: ALWAYS use named timezone (America/Sao_Paulo), NEVER manual offset (-3). **Conversion points in Mesh:** (1) Settlement cutoff check: approval Instant → atZone('America/Sao_Paulo') → localTime → compare with 15:00 → determine base date. (2) Vintage assignment: created_at Instant → atZone('America/Sao_Paulo') → yearMonth → vintage string '2026-03.' (3) Display: approved_at Instant → atZone(user.timezone) → formatted string '13/03/2026 14:30.' (4) Day count: settlement_date (LocalDate) to maturity_date (LocalDate) → businessCalendar.countBusinessDays — no timezone involved (dates, not instants). **DST consideration:** Brazil: no DST since 2019. But: use timezone library (java.time.ZonedDateTime, Python pytz/zoneinfo) that handles ANY timezone correctly, including DST transitions. Why: (a) historical data from before 2019 may have DST. (b) expansion countries may have DST. (c) library handles: developer doesn't need to know rules."
		meshImplication: "Timezone implementation rules: (1) **UTC in all storage** — database: all TIMESTAMPTZ columns in UTC. Application: all Instant objects in UTC. Serialization: ISO 8601 with Z suffix. Deserialization: parse with Z, store as UTC. (2) **explicit timezone conversion** — NEVER implicit timezone. If code needs BRT: val brt = instant.atZone(ZoneId.of('America/Sao_Paulo')). Explicit. Named. Traceable. NEVER: instant.atZone(ZoneId.systemDefault()). Because: systemDefault varies by: server location, container configuration, CI environment, developer machine. Code that uses systemDefault: works on developer machine (BRT), breaks in production (UTC), or vice versa. Deployment-dependent behavior: unacceptable for financial system. (3) **server timezone = UTC** — all application servers, containers, CI environments: TZ=UTC environment variable. Prevents: accidental use of server local time. If server is in São Paulo (BRT): LocalDateTime.now() without zone → gets BRT (implicit). If server is in US-East (EST): gets EST. If server is in cloud (UTC): gets UTC. 3 different results for same code depending on deployment. Fix: TZ=UTC everywhere + explicit conversion when needed. (4) **DST handling** — use timezone library (java.time for Kotlin/Java, zoneinfo for Python 3.9+) that handles DST transitions via IANA tz database. NEVER: manual offset calculation ('UTC-3 for BRT'). Because: during DST (pre-2019 Brazil, or expansion countries), offset changes (UTC-3 → UTC-2). Manual calculation: breaks at transition. Library: handles automatically. Update: tz database updated periodically (new releases when countries change DST rules). (5) **testing** — test across timezone boundaries: operation approved at 23:30 UTC (20:30 BRT) → same BRT business day. Operation at 02:30 UTC (23:30 BRT) → still same BRT date. Operation at 03:00 UTC (00:00 BRT next day) → next BRT business day. Property-based test: for any Instant, businessDate(instant, 'America/Sao_Paulo') is deterministic AND does not depend on System.getDefaultTimezone(). (6) **CLAUDE.md** — 'timestamps: UTC always (TIMESTAMPTZ with Z). Server: TZ=UTC. Timezone conversion: EXPLICIT with ZoneId.of('...'). NEVER ZoneId.systemDefault(). NEVER LocalDateTime.now() without explicit zone. NEVER manual UTC offset (-3). Business timezone for cutoff/vintage: America/Sao_Paulo.' Anti-pattern: server running in cloud region with UTC timezone. Developer tests locally with BRT system timezone. Code: LocalDateTime.now() → developer sees BRT (correct for their context). In production: UTC (wrong for business logic). Cutoff check: compares UTC time against 15:00 BRT cutoff → always wrong (3 hours off). Settlement dates: systematically incorrect. Every operation: affected."
		dependsOn: ["tm-temporal-primitives"]
		rationale: "UTC as single source 2024+. Timezone conversion points 2024+. Na Mesh, UTC everywhere except exactly 3 conversion points (cutoff check, vintage assignment, display). Server TZ=UTC. Explicit conversion. Never manual offset. Never implicit system timezone. Deployment-independent: same code produces same result regardless of where server runs."
	},
	{
		id:         "tm-temporal-integrity-testing"
		name:       "Testes de Integridade Temporal: Provar que Tempo Está Correto em Todo Cenário"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "quarterly"
		definition: "Temporal logic is notoriously hard to test with example-based tests alone. Developers write test: 'approval on Wednesday 14:00 → settlement Thursday.' Test passes. But: doesn't test Friday 16:30 (after cutoff + weekend), or Wednesday before Carnaval (4 consecutive non-business days), or Dec 31 23:59 UTC (which BRT date?), or Feb 29 in leap year. Conceito de 'temporal property-based testing' (2024+): instead of specific examples, define PROPERTIES that must hold for ALL temporal inputs, then generate thousands of random inputs and verify property. Properties: (1) **settlement is always business day** — for any approval Instant: settlementDate is NEVER weekend, NEVER holiday. (2) **settlement ≥ approval date** — settlement never BEFORE approval (time doesn't go backward). (3) **day count is non-negative** — countBusinessDays(start, end) ≥ 0 when end ≥ start. (4) **discount is bounded** — 0 ≤ discount ≤ faceValue (discount can't be negative or exceed face value). (5) **cutoff is deterministic** — same Instant → same settlement date (no randomness, no external state dependency). (6) **timezone consistency** — businessDate(instant, zone) produces same result regardless of server's system timezone. These 6 properties: proven for 10,000 random inputs, catch virtually every temporal edge case that manual tests miss."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, temporal property tests: **(1) Settlement is business day:** forAll { approval <- genInstant(2026) }: val sd = calculateSettlementDate(approval, BRT, cutoff_15h, D+1, 'BR'). assert(businessCalendar.isBusinessDay(sd, 'BR')). Catches: settlement on Saturday (weekend), settlement on Carnaval (holiday), settlement on state holiday. **(2) Settlement ≥ approval:** forAll { approval <- genInstant(2026) }: val sd = calculateSettlementDate(approval, ...). assert(sd >= approval.toLocalDate(BRT)). Catches: negative settlement (time travel bug). **(3) Day count non-negative:** forAll { (start, end) <- genDatePair() where end >= start }: assert(businessCalendar.countBusinessDays(start, end, 'BR') >= 0). Catches: negative day count from date order bug. **(4) Discount bounded:** forAll { (face, rate, days) <- genPricingInputs() }: val d = calculateDiscount(face, rate, days, BUSINESS_252). assert(d.amount >= 0 && d.amount <= face.amount). Catches: negative discount, discount exceeding face value. **(5) Cutoff determinism:** forAll { approval <- genInstant(2026) }: val sd1 = calculateSettlementDate(approval, ...). val sd2 = calculateSettlementDate(approval, ...). assert(sd1 == sd2). Catches: non-deterministic settlement (e.g., using current time in calculation). **(6) Timezone independence:** forAll { approval <- genInstant(2026) }: withSystemTimezone('UTC') { val sd1 = calculateSettlementDate(approval, ...) }. withSystemTimezone('US/Eastern') { val sd2 = calculateSettlementDate(approval, ...) }. assert(sd1 == sd2). Catches: code using system default timezone."
		meshImplication: "Temporal testing implementation: (1) **property tests in CI** — all 6 properties: run with 10,000 iterations on every build. Generators: produce Instants uniformly distributed across 2026 (all months, all days of week, all hours). If any property fails: merge blocked. Non-negotiable. (2) **temporal edge case catalog** — mesh-spec /tests/temporal-edge-cases.md. Known edge cases with tests: Dec 31 Friday → D+1 = Jan 3 Monday (year crossing + weekend). Carnaval Tuesday → D+1 = Wednesday (after multi-day holiday). Feb 28 in non-leap year (month boundary). Feb 29 in leap year (extra day). Approval at exactly cutoff time (boundary). Approval at 02:59 UTC = 23:59 BRT (date boundary — still today in BRT). Approval at 03:00 UTC = 00:00 BRT (next BRT day). Each: documented + automated test. New temporal bug in production: added to catalog. (3) **clock injection for testing** — NEVER: test depends on system clock (LocalDateTime.now(), Instant.now()). ALWAYS: inject clock (Clock.fixed(instant) in Kotlin/Java, freezegun in Python). Tests: deterministic regardless of when they run. Test that passes Tuesday but fails Friday (because cutoff logic depends on day-of-week): BUG in test (should inject specific day). (4) **production temporal monitoring** — canary assertions: alert if settlement date falls on non-business day (should NEVER happen after proper implementation). Alert if day count produces negative (should NEVER happen). Alert if discount > face value (should NEVER happen). These: continuous proof that temporal logic is correct in production. If triggered: immediate investigation (calendar data wrong? Code regression? Edge case not covered?). (5) **CLAUDE.md** — 'temporal logic: ALWAYS test with property-based tests (minimum 6 properties). ALWAYS inject clock (never use system clock in tests). Edge cases: add to /tests/temporal-edge-cases.md when discovered. Production: canary assertions for impossible temporal states.' Anti-pattern: test that passes because it ran on Tuesday (weekday, no special logic triggered), fails on Friday (cutoff + weekend logic differs). Or: test that passes in 2026 but fails in 2027 (hardcoded year in test data). Or: test that passes on developer machine (BRT timezone) but fails in CI (UTC timezone)."
		dependsOn: ["tm-temporal-primitives", "tm-settlement-windows", "tm-day-count-and-accrual", "tm-cutoff-and-batch-cycles", "tm-timezone-discipline"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-testing-and-validation-for-financial-systems"
			conceptId: "tv-property-based-testing"
			context:   "TV defines property-based testing methodology for financial invariants (generators, shrinking, seed persistence). TM extends with temporal-specific properties: settlement is business day, day count is non-negative, cutoff is deterministic, timezone is consistent. TV provides PBT methodology and infrastructure; TM provides temporal-specific properties. Together: financial correctness (TV conservation, idempotency) + temporal correctness (TM settlement, day count) both proven for arbitrary inputs."
		}]
		rationale: "Temporal property-based testing 2024+. Na Mesh, 6 temporal properties proven for 10,000 random inputs: catches Carnaval edge case, year-crossing edge case, timezone-boundary edge case, cutoff-boundary edge case. Manual tests: might test 5-10 specific dates. PBT: tests thousands including edges that no human would enumerate."
	},
	{
		id:         "tm-vintage-and-cohort-temporality"
		name:       "Temporalidade de Safra e Cohort: Agrupamento Temporal para Análise de Performance"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "property"
		reviewCadence: "quarterly"
		definition: "Conceito de 'vintage analysis' (credit risk standard, used by rating agencies, regulators, and FIDC gestors): agrupar operações por período de originação (safra/vintage) e acompanhar performance ao longo do tempo. Safra Q1-2026: todas operações originadas Jan-Mar 2026. Acompanhar: taxa de inadimplência, velocidade de liquidação, performance vs modelo — per safra. Permite: (a) comparar safras (Q1 vs Q2 — performance melhorou ou piorou?), (b) detectar drift (safras recentes performando pior que modelo previu — scoring miscalibrated?), (c) calibrar modelo (model predicted 2% default for Q1 — actual was 3% — recalibrate). Conceito de 'temporal grain for analysis' (2024+): granularidade temporal afeta insights. Safra mensal: mais granular (detecta mudanças rápidas, mas mais ruído estatístico — poucos dados por mês = variance alta). Safra trimestral: menos granular (mais estável, detecta tendências com confiança). Safra anual: para comparação macro. Mesh: safra mensal por default (granular o suficiente para detecção precoce), agregável para trimestral/anual em relatórios. Conceito de 'vintage maturation curve' (2024+): cada safra é observada ao longo do tempo. Safra March-2026 at age 30 days: default rate X%. At age 60 days: Y%. At age 90 days: Z%. Curve: shows how defaults accumulate over time for each vintage. Compare curves across vintages: are newer vintages performing better or worse than older at same age? This is THE fundamental tool for FIDC portfolio management."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, vintage analysis: **Vintage assignment rule:** operation.vintage = operation.created_at.atZone('America/Sao_Paulo').toYearMonth(). Example: operation created 2026-04-01T01:30:00Z. In UTC: April 1. In BRT (UTC-3): 2026-03-31 22:30 = March 31. Vintage: '2026-03' (March — because in BUSINESS timezone it was created in March). NOT '2026-04' (which UTC would give). Timezone matters: using UTC month instead of BRT month moves operations between vintages at month boundaries. Impact: March vintage smaller than reality, April larger. Performance metrics per vintage: distorted. FIDC comparing March vs April: wrong baseline. **Analysis dimensions per vintage:** volume (count of operations, total face value), performance at 30/60/90/180 days (default rate, delinquency rate), pricing (average deságio rate, average spread), composition (sacado concentration HHI, score distribution, average maturity), model calibration (predicted PD at origination vs actual default rate — per score band within vintage). **Temporal comparison pattern:** vintage M vs M-1 (recent trend), vs M-3 (quarterly), vs M-12 (year-over-year). If Q1-2026 default rate 2% and Q2-2026 is 4%: investigate — scoring drift? Market deterioration? Concentration change? Regulatory change? **FIDC reporting:** monthly report includes: vintage performance table (columns: vintage, volume, current balance, 30d delinquency, 60d, 90d, default rate, loss rate). Maturation curve chart: vintages overlaid showing how defaults accumulate by age. Rating agencies (Fitch, Moody's) and CVM: expect vintage analysis in FIDC documentation."
		meshImplication: "Vintage implementation: (1) **vintage assignment at creation** — at operation creation: vintage = created_at.atZone('America/Sao_Paulo').toYearMonth(). Stored: operation.vintage VARCHAR(7) = '2026-03'. Immutable: vintage does NOT change if operation is subsequently modified or corrected. Vintage is 'when was it born,' not 'when was it last updated.' (2) **timezone-correct assignment** — critical: use BRT, not UTC, for month determination. Test: operations created between 00:00-03:00 UTC on 1st of month: vintage should be PREVIOUS month (because 00:00-03:00 UTC = 21:00-24:00 BRT previous day). Property test: vintage assigned consistently with BRT date of creation. (3) **vintage-based queries and indexes** — all analytical queries: filterable and groupable by vintage. WHERE vintage = '2026-03'. GROUP BY vintage ORDER BY vintage. Index: on vintage column (for efficient aggregation on large operation table). (4) **vintage maturation tracking** — for each vintage: track performance at age milestones. Job: monthly, for each vintage that has reached age 30/60/90/180 days: calculate default rate and delinquency rate. Store: maturation_snapshots table {vintage, age_days, default_count, total_count, default_rate, snapshot_date}. (5) **vintage in FIDC reporting** — monthly FIDC report includes: vintage performance table + maturation curve chart. Automated: generated from maturation_snapshots + current operation status. Format: per FIDC regulamento and CVM requirements. (6) **scoring calibration by vintage** — monthly: for each vintage that has matured sufficiently (90+ days): compare model's predicted PD (at origination) with actual default rate. Per score band: if predicted 2% default for score 60-70 band and actual is 5%: model miscalibrated for this score band in this vintage. Action: investigate features, retrain if systematic. (7) **CLAUDE.md** — 'vintage: assigned at creation using BRT timezone. Immutable. Used for: all analytical grouping, FIDC reporting, model calibration. When creating analytical queries: group by vintage, not by arbitrary date ranges.' Anti-pattern: vintage assigned from UTC month. Operation created 2026-04-01 01:30 UTC = 2026-03-31 22:30 BRT. UTC vintage: April. BRT vintage: March. At month boundary (~3% of operations): systematically misassigned. FIDC report: March vintage is undercounted, April is overcounted. Performance per vintage: distorted. Scoring calibration: comparing against wrong vintages. Subtle but systematic error."
		dependsOn: ["tm-temporal-primitives", "tm-timezone-discipline"]
		rationale: "Vintage analysis: credit risk standard expected by FIDC gestors, rating agencies, CVM. Temporal grain 2024+. Vintage maturation curve 2024+. Na Mesh, vintage = month of origination in BRT. Performance tracked per vintage enables: drift detection, model calibration, FIDC reporting, regulatory compliance. Timezone matters: UTC vs BRT month assignment at boundaries affects 3% of operations = systematic distortion."
	},
	{
		id:            "tm-temporal-review"
		name:          "Revisão Temporal: Inventário Periódico de Saúde Temporal do Sistema"
		nature:        "operational"
		role:          "method"
		reviewCadence: "quarterly"
		definition:    "Inventário periódico que verifica: temporal logic is correct and maintained. (1) temporal types — Instant for events, LocalDate for business dates? Any TIMESTAMPTZ for vencimento (should be DATE)? Any VARCHAR for dates? (2) settlement — calculation chain correct? Cutoff applied correctly? Business days from calendar? Settlement shown to fornecedor? (3) bitemporal — scores and compliance preserve history? Corrections create new records (not overwrite)? As-of queries functional? (4) day count — convention matches contract per FIDC? Pricing function using correct formula? Edge cases tested? (5) cutoffs — configured correctly per bank partner? Batch runs on schedule? Period close working? Closed periods immutable? (6) timezone — UTC everywhere in storage? Server TZ=UTC? Explicit conversion at 3 points? No systemDefault() usage? (7) testing — 6 temporal properties passing at 10,000 iterations? Edge case catalog current with any new bugs? Clock injection used (no system clock dependency)? (8) vintage — correctly assigned using BRT timezone? Month boundary test passing? Maturation tracking running?"
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh: revisão trimestral. Settlement date accuracy check + timezone audit + vintage assignment verification."
		meshImplication: "Quarterly (1h): (a) **settlement spot check** — pick 10 random operations from this quarter. For each: verify settlement_date is correct given approval time, cutoff, and calendar. Manual calculation → compare with system. Any discrepancy: investigate + fix. (b) **timezone audit** — grep codebase for: LocalDateTime.now() without zone, ZoneId.systemDefault(), manual offset calculation ('-3', '+0'). Any found: fix. Verify: server TZ=UTC in deployment config. (c) **temporal property tests** — all 6 passing at 10,000 iterations? Any new properties needed (new feature added temporal logic)? Run nightly build report: green? (d) **day count verification** — convention in code: BUSINESS_252. Convention in FIDC contract: business/252. Match: ✓. Pick 3 operations: manually calculate deságio with convention → compare with system value. Must match to centavo. (e) **cutoff verification** — bank batch ran at correct time every day this quarter? Any missed batches? Any operations that missed bank batch despite being before cutoff? (f) **vintage spot check** — pick 5 operations near month boundary (created 00:00-04:00 UTC on 1st of month). Vintage: correct for BRT timezone? (e.g., 02:30 UTC on April 1 = March 31 BRT = March vintage?). (g) **bitemporal** — if implemented: pick 1 score correction from this quarter. Query as-of (before correction date): returns old score? Query as-of (after correction date): returns new score? (h) **edge case catalog** — any temporal incidents this quarter? Added to catalog with automated test? (i) **period close** — monthly close: ran on schedule? Numbers locked? Any retroactive modification attempted and blocked?"
		dependsOn: ["tm-temporal-primitives", "tm-settlement-windows", "tm-bitemporal-modeling", "tm-day-count-and-accrual", "tm-cutoff-and-batch-cycles", "tm-timezone-discipline", "tm-temporal-integrity-testing", "tm-vintage-and-cohort-temporality"]
		rationale: "Temporal logic degrades subtly: new holiday not added to calendar, DST rule changed in expansion country, day count convention drifted from contract, new developer used system default timezone. Quarterly review with manual spot checks: catches drift that automated tests might miss (e.g., calendar data issue, deployment config issue)."
	},
]

reasoningProtocol: [
	{question: "Temporal fields usam Instant (TIMESTAMPTZ UTC) para eventos e LocalDate (DATE) para datas de negócio? Algum vencimento armazenado como timestamp?", reveals: "Se tipos temporais estão corretos — ou se vencimento muda de dia quando timezone é aplicado.", rationale: "Vencimento ≠ timestamp. DATE 2026-03-25: always March 25. TIMESTAMPTZ 2026-03-25T00:00Z: shows March 24 in BRT."},
	{question: "Settlement usa chain completa: Instant → timezone → cutoff → business day addition? Ou date + 1 calendar day?", reveals: "Se settlement é correto em todos os cenários — ou se sexta depois do cutoff calcula Saturday.", rationale: "Settlement chain 2024+. Each step correct → correct result. Skip any → wrong date."},
	{question: "Bitemporal: scores e compliance preservam histórico (what we knew when)? As-of queries distinguem valid time e transaction time?", reveals: "Se regulador pode ser respondido 'what did you know on date X at decision time' — ou se only current state exists.", rationale: "Snodgrass 2000. As-of query: essential for regulatory audit."},
	{question: "Day count convention (business/252) é explícita no contrato E no código? Implementação matches contrato?", reveals: "Se cálculo de deságio é contratualmente correto — ou se convention no código difere (R$11.500/mês de diferença).", rationale: "R$11,50/op difference × 1000 ops = R$11.500/month. Convention must match contract."},
	{question: "Cutoff é configurável e enforced? Period close é immutable? Late data vai para período corrente, não retroativo?", reveals: "Se boundaries temporais são claros e respeitados — ou se operações vazam entre períodos.", rationale: "Period immutability 2024+. Closed period: numbers locked. Corrections: current period."},
	{question: "UTC everywhere exceto 3 pontos de conversão (cutoff, vintage, display)? Server TZ=UTC? Explicit ZoneId?", reveals: "Se timezone é disciplinado e deployment-independent — ou se resultado depende de onde servidor roda.", rationale: "UTC single source 2024+. Server TZ=UTC + explicit conversion = same result everywhere."},
	{question: "Property-based tests para temporal: 6 properties com 10.000 iterations? Clock injection (no system clock)?", reveals: "Se correção temporal é provada para arbitrary inputs — ou se tests são example-based e miss Carnaval/year-crossing.", rationale: "Temporal PBT 2024+: catches edges that manual tests systematically miss."},
]

meshExamples: [
	{
		id:       "ex-settlement-after-cutoff"
		scenario: "Fornecedor submits antecipação. Construtora approves at 16:15 BRT (Thursday). System calculates settlement = Friday (Thursday + 1 day). Bank batch already ran at 16:00. Settlement instruction: not included in Thursday's batch."
		analysis: "No cutoff logic in system. System: D+1 from Thursday = Friday. Reality: Thursday's bank batch ran at 16:00, before the 16:15 approval. Instruction goes into Friday's batch → bank processes Friday → settles Monday (D+1 from Friday in bank's perspective). System shows: Friday. Actual: Monday. Fornecedor: expects Friday, receives Monday. 2 business days late from expectation."
		recommendation: "(1) Implement cutoff: 15:00 BRT (1h before bank batch at 16:00). Approval at 16:15 > 15:00 cutoff → base_date deferred to Friday. D+1 from Friday = Monday. Settlement shown: Monday. Correct. (2) Display at approval: 'Aprovação após horário de corte (15:00). Depósito previsto: segunda-feira 17/03.' Transparent: fornecedor understands the logic. (3) If construtora approves at 14:50 and fornecedor sees 'depósito amanhã': correct (before cutoff). (4) Cutoff boundary: test approval at 14:59 → today. 15:00 → tomorrow. 15:01 → tomorrow. Documented: '≥ 15:00 BRT = next business day.' (5) Monitor: any operation where actual_settlement > calculated_settlement: investigate. Should be zero if cutoff + calendar are correct."
		principlesApplied: ["ax-01", "ax-06"]
		assumptions: ["bank batch at 16:00 is fixed — validate with banking partner, configure per partner", "1h buffer (15:00 cutoff → 16:00 batch) is sufficient — allows 1h for compilation + validation + send"]
		rationale: "Cutoff: prevents mismatch between system promise and banking reality. Without: fornecedor loses trust every time late-day approval shows wrong settlement date. With: settlement date is always achievable."
	},
	{
		id:       "ex-vencimento-timezone-bug"
		scenario: "NF maturity stored as TIMESTAMPTZ: '2026-03-25 00:00:00+00:00' (midnight UTC). Application displays in BRT (UTC-3): '24/03/2026 21:00'. Maturity that should be March 25 displays as March 24 evening."
		analysis: "Root cause: maturity is a DATE concept (which day does the NF expire) stored as TIMESTAMP (a moment in time). UTC midnight March 25 = 9pm March 24 in BRT. When system displays in user's timezone: wrong day. Impact: (a) fornecedor sees maturity as March 24 (1 day earlier than reality). (b) day count calculation may use wrong number of days (off by 1 if using displayed date). (c) 2 participants in same operation may see different maturity dates (one in UTC, one in BRT display)."
		recommendation: "(1) Change maturity_date from TIMESTAMPTZ to DATE. Migration: ALTER TABLE receivables ALTER COLUMN maturity_date TYPE DATE USING maturity_date::date. Safe if all values had time 00:00:00 UTC. (2) After migration: maturity stored as '2026-03-25' (no time, no timezone). Display: always '25/03/2026' regardless of user's timezone. (3) Day count: uses DATE arithmetic (LocalDate → LocalDate). No timezone involved. March 25 is March 25 is March 25. (4) Rule: every vencimento, emissão, validade field → DATE type. Grep for: TIMESTAMPTZ columns that represent dates-without-time. Each: evaluate migration to DATE. (5) Property test: for any maturity DATE value, display in any timezone = same date string (dd/mm/yyyy). This property FAILS for TIMESTAMPTZ (timezone changes display). Passes for DATE (timezone irrelevant). (6) CLAUDE.md: 'vencimento, emissão, validade: DATE type. NEVER TIMESTAMPTZ for business dates that are day-precision concepts.'"
		principlesApplied: ["ax-01", "ax-06"]
		assumptions: ["migration TIMESTAMPTZ→DATE is safe — verify all existing values have 00:00:00 time component", "no business logic depends on time-of-day of maturity — correct, maturity is day-level concept"]
		rationale: "Temporal type discipline. Maturity is a DATE, not a TIMESTAMP. Wrong type: vencimento changes day with timezone. Correct type: 2026-03-25 is always March 25 in every timezone, every display, every calculation."
	},
	{
		id:       "ex-day-count-contract-mismatch"
		scenario: "Contract says 'deságio calculado por dias úteis/252.' Code implements actual/360 (calendar days ÷ 360). For 30-calendar-day operation with 22 business days: contract says (1+rate)^(22/252)-1. Code says rate×30/360."
		analysis: "Two differences: (a) exponential (business/252) vs linear (actual/360). (b) 22 business days vs 30 calendar days. For R$50.000 at 13,75% a.a.: contract method: (1.1375)^(22/252)-1 = 1.123% → deságio R$561,50. Code method: 0.1375×30/360 = 1.146% → deságio R$573,00. Delta: R$11,50 per operation. Code overcharges by R$11,50. × 1.000 ops/month = R$11.500/month overcharging all fornecedores."
		recommendation: "(1) Fix code to match contract: BUSINESS_252 exponential. calculateDiscount: (1+rate)^(businessDays/252)-1. (2) Audit: recalculate all historical operations with correct formula. Any overcharged: credit difference to fornecedor. (3) Contract-code alignment check: add to quarterly review (CL lens). Pricing convention in code MUST match FIDC regulamento + cessão contract. (4) Testing: for sample operations, manually calculate with contract formula → compare with code. Must match to centavo. Property test: discount calculated with BUSINESS_252 differs from ACTUAL_360 (ensures conventions are distinct, not accidentally equivalent). (5) CLAUDE.md: 'pricing formulas MUST match contract convention. When implementing: verify against FIDC regulamento. Default: BUSINESS_252 unless explicitly different.'"
		principlesApplied: ["ax-01", "ax-06"]
		assumptions: ["R$11,50 per operation is significant at scale — yes, ×1000 = R$11.500/month", "historical overcharges are recoverable — yes, recalculate with correct formula and credit", "business/252 is correct convention — yes, standard for CDI-linked FIDC operations"]
		rationale: "Contract-code alignment for day count convention. R$11,50/operation × scale = significant financial error. Wrong convention: breach of contract + fornecedor overpaying + regulatory risk. Fix: code matches contract. Verify: quarterly."
	},
	{
		id:       "ex-vintage-timezone-misassignment"
		scenario: "Operation created at 2026-04-01T01:30:00Z. UTC month: April. BRT: 2026-03-31 22:30 = March. System assigns vintage '2026-04' using UTC. FIDC report: operation in April vintage. FIDC gestor: 'this should be March — it was created on March 31.'"
		analysis: "Vintage assigned from UTC month (April 1 UTC). Business month (BRT): March 31. Operation 'moved' from March to April vintage by timezone error. Impact: March vintage undercounted (missing this operation). April overcounted. Vintage performance metrics: distorted for both months. At month boundary: ~3% of operations affected (operations created 00:00-03:00 UTC = 21:00-24:00 BRT previous day). Over time: systematic bias in vintage analysis."
		recommendation: "(1) Vintage assignment: use BRT. vintage = created_at.atZone('America/Sao_Paulo').toYearMonth(). This operation: March 31 BRT → vintage '2026-03.' Correct. (2) All date-based analytical grouping: convert to BRT before grouping. Not just vintage: daily volume charts, weekly reports, monthly summaries — all use BRT date. (3) Test: for operations created 00:00-03:00 UTC on 1st of each month in 2026: verify vintage = previous month. Property test: vintage assignment is consistent with BRT date. (4) Document: 'vintage is assigned by BRT date of creation, not UTC.' In mesh-spec temporal-types.md and CLAUDE.md. (5) FIDC report: vintage '2026-03' includes all operations created in March BRT — which may include UTC timestamps in early hours of April 1."
		principlesApplied: ["ax-01", "ax-06"]
		assumptions: ["FIDC expects BRT-based vintage — yes, Brazilian business convention", "01:30 UTC = 22:30 BRT previous day — correct for America/Sao_Paulo (UTC-3, no DST since 2019)", "3% of operations affected — approximate, depends on distribution of creation times"]
		rationale: "Timezone for vintage: business convention (BRT), not storage convention (UTC). Misassignment: distorts vintage analysis used by FIDC for risk assessment, model calibration, and regulatory reporting. Fix: 1 line of code (use BRT zone). Impact: correctness of all vintage-based analytics."
	},
]

